<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Work Takes the Wind
   Out of a Weekend Sailor
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Regarding your Aug. 31 Enterprise story "Fiberglass's Long
Life Is Sinking Sailboat Producers," I don't agree with the
contention that the sailboat industry is suffering from
"design constipation" and that all it needs is an infusion of
innovative design to free it from diminishing sales figures.
   My experience from retailing more than 4,000 fiberglass
boats and having represented more than 50 national
manufacturers the past 20 years that have gone belly up,
leads me to somewhat other conclusions. One concerns the
significant lifestyle change of the 25-to-40-year-olds. With
a majority of the families having both partners working full
time, there is not the time to sail on weekends. The careful
planning necessary to juggle a weekend family junket aboard a
sailboat, such as food preparation, fueling, trip planning,
marina reservations, weather, balancing children's lessons
and other family commitments, requires hours of time not
available anymore to the nonexistent "stay-at-home" member of
the family. Making boats go faster or simpler to operate will
not bring back the market. Only a return to a former familial
life style will, and this is not likely in the near future.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Rieders
   Havencraft of New England Inc.
   Sudbury, Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900921-0144
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900921-0144.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Texas Instruments
   Sues Dell, Alleging
   Violation of Patent
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   TXN DELL
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Adding to an already long list of companies it
is suing for patent infringement, computer-chip giant Texas
Instruments Inc. filed suit last Thursday against mail-order
computer firm Dell Computer Corp.
   TI asked the U.S. District Court for the Northern District
of Texas to assess a dollar amount for damages, claiming that
Dell, of Austin, Texas, violated several key patents in
building its personal computers. "People who make PC clones
generally violate our patents," a TI spokesman said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   TI and Dell had been discussing patent issues since April.
"We were very surprised when they filed," said a Dell
spokesman.
   Dell says the suit is without merit -- merely another
example of TI's overactive legal department. Within the past
year, TI has sued its own customers and competing U.S. chip
firms on patent-related matters. Among those companies are
Zenith Data Systems Corp., Analog Devices Inc. and LSI Logic
Corp.
   Dell is the second Texas computer maker this month to spar
in court over patents with TI. Tandy Corp. on Sept. 6 alleged
that TI broke federal antitrust laws by falsely claiming
ownership of certain microprocessor technologies. Tandy also
alleged that TI demanded unreasonably high royalty payments.
   Japanese chip firms have also accused TI of demanding
exorbitant royalty rates. A Japanese press report said TI
demanded 10% of the wholesale value of products using chips
based on a TI patent. TI would not confirm the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900921-0143
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900921-0143.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Gorbachev's Stall
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   President Gorbachev seemed unambiguous enough last week
when he threw his support behind the more radical of two
approaches for attacking the Soviet Union's economic crisis,
but now he's temporizing.
   On Monday the president decided that a national referendum
would be necessary on a crucial element of the program: land
ownership. In other words, Soviet citizens must be asked if
they think that they should be allowed to own land.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A referendum would take months, postponing the program put
together by Professor Stanislav Shatalin -- a 500-day
timetable for curbing state spending, eliminating subsidies
to state-owned industrial and agricultural enterprises and
putting land into private hands. And delay could doom the
effort entirely. The Soviet Union is slipping into anarchy.
It may soon be too late for organized reform.
   This is not the first time that Mr. Gorbachev has avoided
the most direct route between two points. Perestroika has
thus far been a bust because Mr. Gorbachev refuses to follow
the logic of reform to its necessary conclusions. The whole
world sees that the Soviet Union must move toward free
markets.
   But advocates of the go-slow approach, led up by Premier
Nikolai Ryzhkov, still managed to convince Mr. Gorbachev that
the union is endangered by the Shatalin plan. Mr. Ryzhkov
even told a reporter that if his own program is rejected, "I
will not carry out any other." He's worried that the program,
which would start October 1, would stack the cards in favor
of secessionist republics. Last week the prime minister said,
on Soviet television monitored by the BBC, that the proposal
to pay taxes exclusively at the local and republic level
"means the elimination of the U.S.S.R. as a single state. The
government will not accept this path."
   Boris Yeltsin, the head of the Russian Republic, is fully
aware of this. He knows that the disintegration of the Soviet
Union would leave him in control of a superpower, arguably
more manageable and more potent than the current U.S.S.R. The
Russian Federation has already adopted the Shatalin plan, and
Mr. Yeltsin's supporters are evidently ready to turn Moscow
upside down on behalf of a radical overhaul.
   But don't underestimate Mikhail Gorbachev; he too knows
how to read political tea leaves. By siding with orthodoxy
after all, he is saying in effect that he has little faith in
the radicals' solution. One could say that his two kopeck's
worth of support last week for the program was grossly
overvalued. The president as obliquely as ever is now casting
his ever-variable vote with those who would preserve the
empire and their own positions of power in it.
   These sudden turns in events at the highest levels of the
Soviet government help one understand the depth of feeling
Alekandr Solzhenitsyn expressed in his article published in
the Soviet Union this week: "Nothing useful will ever be
reached unless the Communist-Leninist party yields not just
one point of its constitutional power but is completely
separated from any influence on economic and state life,
completely gives up control over us or any aspect of our
lives."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900921-0142
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900921-0142.
</DOCID>
