<HL>
   Resistance Grows
   To Plan to Boost
   FHA Loan Costs
   ----
   By Joe Davidson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
</IN>
<GV>
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Consumer and industry groups alike are
fighting a Bush administration plan that would boost up-front
costs for borrowers of loans backed by the Federal Housing
Administration.
   The plan is designed to protect the solvency of the FHA's
mutual mortgage insurance fund, which insures low
down-payment mortgages on single-family homes. Officials of
the Department of Housing and Urban Development, citing a
study by Price Waterhouse, say the fund isn't operating on a
sound basis, in part because of poor management and lax
monitoring during the Reagan administration. The officials
predict that the fund will be insolvent by the middle of the
decade.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The administration, among other things, wants to add a
0.5% premium to high-risk loans and require home buyers to
pay two-thirds of the closing costs in cash at settlement.
The HUD plan would eliminate as many as 100,000 borrowers
annually, according to the National Association of Realtors.
   The Senate housing bill has incorporated the
administration's plan. But a different proposal, which is
backed by several trade and consumer groups, is contained in
legislation passed by the House. The two versions must be
resolved by a conference committee.
   The House version, known as the Vento-Ridge alternative,
would reduce the current up-front premium to 1.35% from 3.8%,
but add a 0.6% annual insurance premium. The up-front cash
needed by home buyers would remain about the same as under
current FHA requirements.
   Currently, the buyer of a house selling for $100,000 would
have to pay $6,600 at settlement. That figure would rise to
$7,866 under the HUD proposal, according to figures released
by the Senate Committee on Banking, Housing and Urban
Affairs.
   Both the HUD plan and the Vento-Ridge alternative would
keep the FHA fund financially stable, according to Price
Waterhouse. Administration officials have said they would
recommend a veto of the House housing legislation, in part
because of its FHA measure.
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp and his aides have met with
industry groups in an attempt to resolve the differences.
"We've been talking with all elements of the industry," said
Mary Brunette, a department spokeswoman. "We're working to
resolve some of the differences so the conference can go
forward."
   Warren Lasko, executive vice president of the Mortgage
Bankers Association, said his organization doesn't believe
the financial troubles of the FHA are as bad as the
administration contends.
   The HUD proposal has made some strange bedfellows of its
opponents. Consumer advocates, such as the Consumer's Union
and National People's Action, usually find themselves on the
opposite side of issues from trade associations such as the
National Association of Realtors.
   "It's one of those issues where their profit interest in
putting people in houses parallels our interest in putting
people in houses," said Michelle Meier of the Consumer's
Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900921-0054
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900921-0054.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   World Markets:
   Tokyo Stocks Fall for Sixth Session in a Row,
   As Interest Rate-Sensitive Sectors Lead Decline
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tokyo stock prices fell for the sixth consecutive trading
day Thursday to the year's low, with the pace of declines set
by interest rate-sensitive sectors.
   In London, shares closed lower after tumbling from an
opening high and breaking through two main support levels.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo's Nikkei Index of 225 issues was down 123.19 points,
or 0.52%, at 23602.98.
   In Tokyo Friday, the Nikkei index fell another 310.18
points to close the morning session at 23292.80.
   On Thursday, stock prices rebounded from morning lows
during the afternoon session with help from small-volume
index-linked buying by investment trust funds and securities
companies, traders said.
   But institutional buying thinned further, amid continuing
uncertainty about the direction of domestic interest rates
and the Mideast situation. Some investors also raised cash
positions ahead of Japan's long weekend, traders said. Tokyo
markets will be closed Monday for a national holiday.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 400 million
shares, in line with 390 million shares Wednesday. Losers
outnumbered gainers 754 to 191, while 156 issues were
unchanged.
   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed in the
first section fell 31.75 points, or 1.76%, to 1767.97.
   The second section index dropped 55.20 points, or 1.60%,
to 3394.54. Volume in the section was estimated at 6.7
million shares, compared with almost seven million shares
Wednesday.
   "We want to support the market by active buying if
possible," said an official at Nikko Securities.
   But with the fiscal midyear book closing at the end of
September, trading activity of brokerage houses will be
restricted much like that of other major players including
financial institutions, he said.
   With little buying support, stocks remained vulnerable
even to only a small amount of general selling as well as
arbitrage selling, traders said.
   As many companies evaluate the value of holdings based on
stock prices on the last day of September, participants said,
some window dressing operations by brokerage houses and
institutions are expected to push up stock prices Sept. 28,
the last trading day of the month.
   "Many expect the Nikkei to move up around 25000 or 26000
points {on Sept. 28}," a trader at Daiwa Securities said.
   But in the longer term, volume is likely to remain poor,
making it difficult for stocks to rebound strongly.
   "Being cautious is the best thing to do," said Hironobu
Hagio, manager of the equity division at Nippon Life
Insurance.
   Unless domestic interest rates peak out or the Persian
Gulf problem is solved, institutions are unable to commit
themselves to the stock market, he said.
   "It is true that we are waiting for a buying opportunity.
But as long as there is a possibility that stock prices may
fall further, we can't buy," Mr. Hagio said.
   The most heavily traded issue Thursday was Kobe Steel,
with a total of 18 million of its shares changing hands. Kobe
Steel gained 4 yen to 539 yen ($3.92).
   While financial issues are likely to come under further
pressure, shares that have been oversold, such as steels,
shipbuildings and paper-pulps, are expected to show technical
rebounds soon, said Hisamichi Sawa, vice president at
Prudential-Bache Securities (Japan).
   Real estate shares were sold Thursday as a government
report on the latest nationwide land price data showed the
sharpest yearly growth on record, of an average 13.7%, in the
year ended July 1.
   The report prompted speculation that the government will
continue to pressure the real estate industry to keep land
prices from rising, traders said.
   Mitsubishi Estate was down 70 yen at 1140 yen, while
Sumitomo Realty dropped 30 yen to 1060 yen.
   Blue-chip electrics with strong earnings predictions also
failed to get support because of the lack of buy orders,
traders said.
   Sony fell 110 yen to 6550 yen. Sharp dropped 40 yen to
1280 yen, while Matsushita Electric Industrial declined 50
yen to 1610 yen.
   In London, the market fell through support levels for the
Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-Share Index at 2050 and
2030 points.
   The suspension of trading in Polly Peck following a
variety of rumors and a free fall in the company's share
price brought the fragile London market down, and was the
main talking point among traders.
   "There is just no investor confidence. No one wants to
invest," one trader said. He added that there was no point in
traders buying when there was no support in the market, and
the prospect was for prices to fall even lower.
   Wall Street slumped during the London afternoon session,
generating additional selling pressure in London.
   The FT-SE 100-Share Index fell 48.9 points to 2016.9,
unable to match an opening high of 2069.2. The Financial
Times 30-Share Index closed down 45.1 points at 1531.0.
Volume was 517.7 million shares, well above Wednesday's 386.8
million.
   Polly Peck shares were suspended at 108 pence ($2.04)
after a 135-pence fall from the Wednesday close. Rumors were
rampant, and the company wasn't commenting on the reasons for
the suspension except to say that it wanted to stop the
stock's free fall.
   Meanwhile, Beazer fell 15 pence to 93 pence. The
construction company said it wasn't aware of any reason for
the fall, adding that interim results next week should be in
line with market expectations.
   Cookson, a metals, chemicals and plastics maker, fell 36
pence to 54 pence. Cookson was hurt by rumors that it might
not be able to pay an interim dividend.
   Among company results, brewing concern Guinness posted a
31% rise in pretax profit to #322 million. Initial market
enthusiasm was damped, and the shares ended 11 pence lower at
669 pence after a spurt upward at the opening of trading.
   Glaxo also reported strong results. Half-year pretax
profit rose 13% to #1.14 billion, exceeding market forecasts.
But again, the initial enthusiasm faded, and the shares ended
5 pence lower at 716 pence.
   Meanwhile, shares closed lower in all major European
markets. South African gold stocks closed narrowly mixed.
   And stocks closed lower in Sydney, Singapore, Seoul and
Taipei, mixed in Hong Kong, higher in Manila, and little
changed in Wellington.
                                                                                                       

   Here are price trends on the world's major stock markets,
as calculated by Morgan Stanley Capital International
Perspective, Geneva. To make them directly comparable, each
index is based on the close of 1969 equaling 100. The
percentage change is since year-end.
                                                                                                       

