<HL>
   Business Brief -- American Telephone &amp; Telegraph:
   Telmex Fiber-Optic Contract
   For $130 Million Is Won
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   T LATAM TFONY ERIYD F.CIU
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. made its first major
entry into the Mexican market by winning a $130 million
contract from Telefonos de Mexico S.A. de C.V., Mexico's
national telephone company.
   AT&amp;T, based in New York, will build a major part of a
fiber optic network that will link 54 locations throughout
the country, significantly enhancing Mexico's international
long-distance infrastructure.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The contract is a coup for AT&amp;T, whose other major
contract with Telmex was a $13 million project involving
digital access and cross connecting equipment.
   AT&amp;T outbid two of Mexico's largest traditional suppliers,
L.M. Ericsson of Sweden and Alcatel of France, to win the
right to build 60% of the network. Alcatel has been awarded a
contract to build 25% of the network and Ericsson 15%.
   The Mexican project begins this month and will be
completed by 1993. It involves 8,000 miles of fiber-optic
cable and related equipment. AT&amp;T and its Spanish subsidiary
will provide the cable, components, and transmission
equipment. AT&amp;T will also be working with a Mexican
engineering and construction firm to provide Telmex with a
turnkey system.
   The project will create one of the most modern telephone
networks in the world, offering high-quality transmission,
faster connection speeds and a larger call handling capacity.
</TEXT>
