<HL>
   Federal Express
   Posts 42% Rise
   In 1st-Period Net
   ----
   By Michael J. McCarthy
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<CO>
   FDX
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
AIR FREIGHT (AIF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Federal Express Corp. reported a 42% gain in net income
for its first quarter, ended Aug. 31, on a 16% gain in
revenue.
   The Memphis, Tenn., express-delivery company said net was
$43.1 million, or 81 cents a share, compared with $30.4
million, or 58 cents a share. Revenue rose to $1.92 billion
from $1.65 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The per-share earnings exceeded analysts' estimates, but
there were several one-time items that contributed to the
results.
   "It was seemingly a good quarter," said Kevin Murphy, an
analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. "But there were some
materially significant items in there as well."
   For one thing, Federal Express gained some charter
business from the U.S. military's Operation Desert Shield
buildup of troops and equipment in the Middle East. It also
picked up some shipments that would have gone to rival United
Parcel Service of America Inc., as some customers shifted
their business amid fears of a strike at UPS during the
quarter. Earnings also benefited from the sale of
noise-reduction kits for aircraft engines.
   On an operating basis, Federal attributed the earnings
increase to cost-control efforts and productivity
improvements. It also said there was a "modest rebound" in
Asian air freight volume from the depressed levels of April
and May.
   A company spokesman said Federal Express had another loss
on its international business, which has been going through a
costly expansion process, but he wouldn't elaborate.
   Analysts said the U.S. operations' results were more
promising. "The domestic side of the house looks very strong,
even with weak volume, because of the much higher margins
they're getting" as a result of price increases this year,
said Doug Arthur, an analyst at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.
   To cover rising fuel costs caused by the Mideast showdown
with Iraq, Federal said it will raise some prices on most
overseas routes before the end of the year. It said the
increases will vary by route but will be within the company's
usual 3% to 7% range. The spokesman said he expects some
international competitors to follow suit.
   In the U.S., Federal Express said it won't raise prices
further in its small package express business. The company
has increased those prices twice this year, by 4% to 5% in
April and 1% to 2% in July.
   Federal Express said its fuel costs were in line with
expectations during the latest quarter but will be hurt by
higher prices as current fuel contracts expire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900921-0020
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900921-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Significant Leakage of Food to Iraq
   Seen by Agriculture Department Aides
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<GV>
AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT (AGD)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Agriculture Department analysts, in a break
with the Bush administration's high expectations of choking
off trade with Iraq, are projecting considerable leakage in
the food embargo against the embattled nation.
   The department's World Agricultural Outlook Board
estimates that despite the international embargo, Iraq will
be able to import one million metric tons of wheat and wheat
flour between last July 1 and June 30, 1991, about one-fourth
of what it customarily uses annually. The panel also projects
Iraq will import 350,000 metric tons of rice next year,
almost half of its annual consumption. In addition, the panel
expects Iraqi imports of barley and other coarse grains to
total 400,000 metric tons between Oct. 1 and Sept. 30, 1991.
Typically, Iraq uses about 1.4 million metric tons of barley
a year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yesterday, several grain traders and a senior Treasury
official were skeptical of the panel's projections. But
should the estimates prove correct, it suggests the regime of
Saddam Hussein could hold out longer than has been generally
thought.
   The panel's forecast assumes that much of the food will be
smuggled into Iraq by truck, ship, even camel caravan, and
that some will be provided openly by famine-relief
organizations under United Nations auspices.
   "There are a lot of traders in the Mideast who really
don't have any flag," said Gerald Rector, chairman of the
outlook board's feed grains and wheat committee. "They will
take a commodity wherever they can get the best price."
   The board's surprising forecast represents the first
disquieting government assessment of the prospects for
embargo-busting since Iraq's Aug. 2 invasion of Kuwait and
the swift imposition of U.N. sanctions against Baghdad.
Administration officials have repeatedly extolled the
cooperation of other nations in honoring and enforcing the
sanctions, and they have cited Iraqi bread lines and
shortages of sugar, cooking oil and other commodities as
proof that the embargo is beginning to bite.
   In an interview yesterday, Deputy Treasury Secretary John
Robson described the international sanctions as "an amazingly
tight net," and dismissed the possibility of imports'
slipping through in any appreciable volume.
   "I don't think you're going to have an absolutely
air-tight embargo," he said, "but I'm not going to sit around
and worry about a truckload of tomatoes getting in."
   The outlook board members are analysts with the Foreign
Agricultural Service and Economic Research Service, who tap
the expertise of U.S. officials outside the Agriculture
Department in making projections of world agricultural trade.
   The board expects Iraq to devote part of its diminishing
foreign exchange to rice purchases. In its Sept. 12 report,
the panel projects Iraqi rice imports for 1991 at 350,000
tons, just 100,000 tons less than what was imported this year
before sanctions were imposed.
   "Rice should be the primary commodity they try to bring
in," said Mr. Rector. "Typically, it's traded in bag form.
You can put it on a camel or a boat and bring it in."
   As for the one-million-metric-ton forecast for wheat and
wheat flour, an estimated 300,000 tons were imported before
Iraq was embargoed, he said. The panel assumes that the
current glut of wheat on the world market will help Iraqi
efforts to obtain through middlemen an additional 700,000
tons.
   "If you've got a lot of wheat looking for a home," said
Mr. Rector, "it makes it more likely that you have people
willing to buy it and get it across the {Iraqi} border."
   The board expects nations such as Libya and Yemen to help
Iraq by serving as transshipment points for food purchased
elsewhere, Mr. Rector said. In addition, leakage is expected
across the Jordanian, Turkish and Iranian borders. The
shipments would take roundabout routes, he added. One
possibility foreseen: Persian Gulf traders would ferry grain
by boat into Iran, and Iranian truckers would take it across
the border.
   "Iran and Iraq traded across the border even when they
were fighting" in their eight-year war that ended in 1988, he
said.
   If the Iraqis import as much food as the analysts
forecast, the odds of their holding out until next year's
harvests would be improved considerably. Last month, an
Agriculture Department report estimated that Iraq already had
enough wheat, rice, barley and other coarse grains to last
four to six months.
   Several grain-trade experts expressed doubts about the
willingness of any nation to engage in embargo-busting in the
face of overwhelming world support for the sanctions. "I
can't imagine what country would load {grain}," said Bernard
Steinweg, a Continental Grain Co. executive. "That would be a
ridiculous risk."
   Furthermore, grain traders for multinational agribusiness
companies would detect any big shipments, said a Cargill Inc.
spokesman, who added that the entire market acts as an
"intelligence network."
   Some Agriculture Department officials are also skeptical
about the potential for leakage. "Shiploads of grain are easy
to see," said one official. "Truckloads going across the
border may be happening, but they won't make a big dent {in
the embargo}.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900921-0019
</DOCNO>
