<HL>
   CalFed Set to Sell
   Unit to Conseco Inc.
   For $140.2 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
09/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   CAL CNC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
LIFE INSURANCE (INL)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- CalFed Inc. said it will sell its annuity
and life insurance subsidiary to Conseco Inc., a Carmel,
Ind., insurance firm, for about $140.2 million.
   As a result of the sale, Calfed said it has established a
provision for a loss of about $40 million in the third
quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the agreement, CalFed will sell Beneficial Standard
Life Incurance Company to Conseco in exchange for cash.
CalFed will purchase about $25 million of real estate and
other assets owned by Beneficial Standard. In addition, in
the three months after the sale, CalFed may choose to buy an
additional $35 million of other real estate assets that its
insurance unit acquired through foreclosure, as well as some
nonperforming and other mortgage loans.
   About $12 million of the $40 million loss expected
involved tax liabilities incurred in the sale, a CalFed
spokesman said. The rest of the loss is the result of the
company's repurchase of some of Beneficial Standard's assets.
   "There will definitely be an impact on earnings," the
spokesman said. CalFed will report its third-quarter earnings
in mid-October.
   The sale is part of CalFed's two-year effort to
restructure its financial service business, selling
marginally profitable assets and jettisoning side ventures.
Since the summer of 1989, its principal subsidiary,
California Federal Bank, has sold its $125 million credit
card portfolio, and CalFed has sold off several insurance
units, a retirement-plan business and its interests in a
string of real estate properties.
   Last year, Beneficial Standard had a loss of $5.3 million
on revenue of $150.4 million. In the first six months of
1990, it had earnings of $3.5 million. Beneficial Standard
had $1.8 billion in assets as of June 30, 1990.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   UNDER AN AGREEMENT by which CalFed Inc. will sell its
subsidiary, Beneficial Standard Life Insurance Co., to
Conseco Inc., CalFed may purchase back from Beneficial $35
million of real estate assets acquired through foreclosure,
as well as some nonperforming and other mortgage loans within
three years. The period of time was misstated in Friday's
edition.
   (WSJ Sept. 24, 1990)
</TEXT>
